text.text: A Guide to Clapton

It’s commonplace nowadays for bikes and beards to spring to mind when someone starts talking about Hackney, and while some pockets of the borough are kind of swarming with them, Clapton is legit packed with interesting independent businesses and local gems to boot. You know what, we found more here than we know what to do with. There’s only one thing for it... let’s have it XL Clapton!
Best for... a green oasis for the 'gram

tip.text:
We lament the fall of the tram as much as the next app, but that cloud has a silver lining because the old Clapton Tram Depot has been superbly converted into a soothing, beautiful café full of botany, exposed brickwork, ancient beams and parquetry flooring. The owners of this place have really put some time into the aesthetic and we're digging it. They serve breakfast, lunch and also sell a range of organic products from this light-filled space.

Whilst the lunch menu features a couple of toasted sandwiches and a soup of the day, we stopped by for a lazy breakfast where the menu comes with all the classics: Bloody Mary, sourdough, granola, eggs, bacon. Whatever you do, though, get a dish featuring their portobello mushrooms in tarragon and soya cashew cream - you won't regret it. With soft piano music playing overhead, and locals reading the paper and having a chat, this is a green oasis of calm in Clapton.

Best for...a real taste of the East

tip.text:
The Miyazaki influence is strong here: from the ornate, faded wallpaper to the small toy train perpetually travelling on its lonely loop around the cosy little restaurant, My Neighbours The Dumplings is dripping with the same melancholic charm that the Japanese auteur is known for - you half expect Totoro to show up and whisk you away on a fantastical adventure.

But, alas, the only adventure you’ll be going on at MNTD is of the culinary kind. With a menu committed to the dumpling, paying no mind to geographical differences, you can expect all kinds of innovative pan-Asian dishes that are either 1) dumplings, or 2) designed to compliment dumplings (sometimes we think this is what we were designed for). Made fresh everyday, the parcels themselves are delicate and bursting with flavour, with flairs of innovation wherever you look, while punchy side salads and a sake-focused drinks list offer excellent palate cleansers/time fillers between portions.

text.text: Sure, you want the starchy goodness of the dumpling in your mouth, but you don't want to travel to the tourist hellhole that is Chinatown to get it. Fear not, as MND's first permanent outpost serves dim sum-style fare with an emphasis on their fine-ass, handmade dumplings. They also serve specialty dishes made with free-range meat, like the crispy pork belly with homemade plum sauce. Just roll us into a little dumpling and leave us here.
Best for... a scruffy but charming boozer

tip.text:
What was once a boozer with a dodgy rep on the Murder Mile has gradually earned its place in people's hearts as a loveable, slightly scruffy community hub with hella soul. There’s been no million-pound facelift here (or however much pub facelifts cost), instead, you’ll find a creaking tavern with plenty of nooks and crannies adorned in random vintage bits and bobs, worn floorboards, log fires and mismatched furniture.

This is a big pub with the intimacy and charm of a small one: where weekly comedy nights are legendary and a late Saturday night pitstop will be rewarded with an unpretentious raucous dance to Wham or suchlike. Add in one of the biggest beer gardens in East and you’ve got yourself all you require from a neighbourhood boozer.

Best for...natural wine in a classy setting

tip.text:
P. Franco is a bit of an institution on the low intervention wine scene - almost single handedly making 'natural' the coolest wine for Londoners to drink. By day it's a mighty friendly shop stocking unpretentious liquids - of varying price range. (France and Italy dominate the wine offerings but you can still expect a hefty selection of bottles here, from the USA to Australia.)

By night (four a week) it becomes one of the most intimate eating experiences about. Where guest chefs work their magic over two induction hobs and serve up all sorts of goodies to a large communal table. Though cooking styles change depending on who's in the kitchen, you can always expect high calibre grub from these guys - paired with intriguing natural wine selects. Our fave bit? The way beginners and wine geeks are welcomed with equally smiley faces.

Kitchen times:
Thurs: 6-9
Fri-Sat: 6-10
Sun: 2-9

Best for... books (and lots of them)

tip.text:
This sweet and pokey independent bookshop on Lower Clapton Road proves that wonderful things often come in small packages. You’ll find an extensive selection upstairs, ranging from contemporary fiction to gorgeous coffee table books - while the downstairs room, complete with couch, offers vintage Penguin books, first editions and vinyl to boot.

Pages of Hackney also stage a number of events: from book readings to photography exhibitions, and are proud to have hosted talks from the likes of China Mielville and Melissa Benn in the past. Get down and help keep printed word alive!

text.text: We do love stumbling across gems like this here independent bookshop. The great selection in Pages of Hackney will have you book worms wriggling with excitement: peruse the upstairs for the likes of contemporary fiction and gorgeous coffee table books or step into the time warp that is the basement for more singular offerings. Down here you’ll find classic vinyl, weathered orange-spined Penguins and first editions galore.
Best for... catching a flick in style

tip.text:
The unremarkable door leading to a dark flight of stairs next to the Spar on Chatsworth Road does little to prepare you for the eye-popping beauty that awaits at the top. You’ll enter into a dimly lit bar where speckled mirrors, a sweeping curved ceiling, copper pineapple bar lamps and plush, chesterfield benches will transport you through time and space to 1920s Hollywood, and a rendezvous with someone glamorous and seductive. Or that dude you met on Happn.

The art deco aesthetic continues into the theatre where an abundance of red velvet and extremely comfortable armchairs will settle you in nicely. The only risk is feeling so at home that you end up falling asleep - especially with the recommended carafe of Borough Wines’ malbec. £5 tickets on Monday’s ain’t bad either.

Best for... a cheap and tech-free hangout

tip.text:
It's like Britain and Japan got into a fight, made up, then opened up a cafe together. Pacific Social Club describes itself as a drop-out centre and wannabe Izakaya. What does that mean for you? Great coffee and cakes to the soundtrack of vintage vinyls by day, but in the evenings from Thursday to Saturday you have the mighty Japanese Sho Foo Doh kitchen takeover.

We don't know how they came up with this intercontinental mix, but we wish there were more like it.

text.text: Liam felt like cafes had stopped being cheap places to chill out in, so he went and opened the Pacific Social Club in Hackney, a casual hangout first and foremost (laptops and phones can only be used in the back room). All foodstuff costs between £3.50 and £5.50, so your pocket shouldn’t take too much of a hit in here. The soundtrack comes courtesy of his weird and wonderful vinyl collection, while daytime food basically amounts to (nice) things on toast.
Best for...sharing a plate and watching the world go by

tip.text:
Isreali-inspired Bernstein’s Bar is a slice of Tel-Aviv cool sitting on a corner of Chatsworth Road. This is an ideal place to take a seat (inside or on the pavement) and watch the Clapton cool cats pass whilst tucking into hearty Middle Eastern dishes; having a coffee; doing the lazy lunch dance; or dipping the beak in something strong and letting the evening take over.

Sourcing plenty of their bits locally, the cuisine here is the comforting chow of Israel and the Levant: fish, meat and cheese sharing boards alongside filling and tasty soups - the chicken stew is known to cure almost every illness known to man. Serving all sorts for all sorts, it’s another vibey spot to add to Clapton’s growing arsenal.

text.text: We're always happy to see the rarely seen late-night-cafe when we come across one, so Israeli-inspired Bernstein's Bar, sitting on a corner in Chatsworth Road, is really alright by us. This is an ideal place to take a seat (either in or outside on the pavement) and watch the world go by whilst tucking into some of their hearty Middle Eastern dishes. An ideal spot for sharing a fish, cheese or meat board before letting an espresso do its magic.
Best for... yin (vinyl) and yang (coffee)

tip.text: There’s a definite beauty in simple pleasures. Kicking back and listening to wax spin while you sip on a coffee has got to be one of those: swing by here and listen to records in a supremely chilled setting, with coffee from the delightful roasters at All Press and fresh juices on the menu to boot. Drinks might get a little bit stiffer once the sun goes down but you won’t find us complaining about that.

Best for... proper.pizza.piez

tip.text:
The ‘best pizza in London’ debate is never gonna die, but let’s get it straight - Sodo is frickin’ dope pizza. They’ve spread out their dough in East but this is their original HQ: a cosy cubbyhole nestled along Upper Clapton Road that’s all worn woods, greenery, and sumptuous sourdough pies suitably thin, topping-heavy and oozing with flavour.

Combining fresh ingredients, we’d tip either the veggie friendly Lorena (tomato, mozzarella, butternut squash, feta, pine nuts and rosemary) or the less veggie friendly Wicker Man (tomato, mozzarella, 'ndjua, pepperoni, mascarpone and scotch bonnet honey). Capable of being the casual pizzeria for something low key or the date night spot when a lil' romance is needed, it’s an excellent pizza place to drop in on.

text.text: Stumble past the bustling strip that is Lower Clapton Road and find yourself in the ends of Upper Clapton: way up here (it’s not that far) the good people at Sodo have got their heads down and they’re working tirelessly to bring you that truly authentic pizza. They ferment all of their own sourdough for 48 hours and even make their own ice cream and ginger ale. Talk about DIY; these lot ain’t messin’ about in the slightest.
Best for... kneeling at the feet of the God of grocery shops

tip.text: All your grocery needs and then some, Palm 2 (we don’t know of a Palm 1) is much, much more than your local supermarket. You’ll find plenty of local produce on these shelves, including Beavertown beers and Union coffee, while there’s heaps to snack on from the deli section too. Does your corner shop do a Sunday roast? Didn’t think so, but this one does! Tables out front are perfect for soaking up a spot of sun and shooting the shit with your neighbours, while the cheeky coffee window means you can grab a quick one on the go.

text.text: What if your corner shop also whipped up fresh, tasty breakfasts, brunches and Sunday lunches? What if they stocked all your favourite local craft beers? What if they had a lovely upstairs dining room/event space? What if they had a hole-in-the-wall coffee counter? What if they had benches out front for tucking into grub and chin-wagging with pals? Palm 2 is what if.
